`.` is the CTX repository root: an MVP scaffold for an opinionated
agentic coding system, combining a Rust-lint enforcement layer, a
context-tree pipeline, and (deferred) architecture-audit hooks. Depending
on the repo root gets you the workspace manifest and its lint/CI/toolchain
pins, the six-crate implementation, the prompt/agent layers that drive
summarization, and the docs that record why it's built this way — nothing
here is itself consumed by other code; this is the top of the tree.

The dogfood invariant threads through most top-level files: `Cargo.toml`'s
workspace lint table must stay byte-identical to `template/Cargo.toml`
(the scaffold this repo hands out to consumers), and `clippy.toml`,
`rust-toolchain.toml`, `rustfmt.toml`, and `deny.toml` are each pinned
twice — once here, once in `template/` — with the same soft/hard-tier
split (clippy.toml's 80-line/25-complexity hard fail backed by
`scripts/rationale_check.py`'s softer thresholds). Changing any of these
five files means checking whether `template/`'s copy needs the same edit.
`crates/` is where the actual pipeline lives (`ctx-core`'s deny-rule gate,
`ctx-access`, `ctx-summarize`, `ctx-scan`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-check`,
`ctx-verify`, `ctx-cage`); `prompts/` and `agents/` are its two
decoupled-content boundaries (prompt text, model-adapter transport)
that `ctx-summarize` and future auditing depend on without embedding
either in Rust code. `docs/` is the authority on why the architecture
looks this way (SPEC frozen, DECISIONS append-only, STATUS the only
intentionally-stale file); `sandbox/` is fully retired in favor of
`crates/ctx-cage`; `scripts/` supplies the CI checks that `template/`
also copies out; `.claude/` wires `ctx-context` into the live editing
session via a hook.

Two invariants hold repo-wide, not just per-crate: no `#[allow(...)]`
anywhere and no `unsafe`, enforced by lint config with no override
mechanism; and prompt/agent content is never embedded in Rust source —
`ctx-summarize` and any future auditor load `prompts/*.md` and shell out
to `agents/*` rather than hardcoding either. The `intent_divergence:`
label used by rollups/auditor is shared vocabulary between
`prompts/summarizer-rollup.md` and `prompts/auditor.md`; renaming it
in one breaks the other.

README.md's quickstart describes `ctx-access init-task/end-task` as
"once implemented," and Layer 2 is stated as advisory-only pending a
sandbox deploy — both match intent.md's explicit staging, so no
divergence to report at the root level.